@phdthesis{Hopes2011,
abstract = {A large-scale continuous campaign management model-based approach that places value on variables that are broad, difficult to measure, and changing with time (from the perspective of behavioral change) does not exist at this time of writing. This research seeks to identify a model-based approach to continuously optimize an energy efficiency campaign. A literature review of traditional approaches to campaign management finds that behavioral variables, as well as economic variables, are important in campaign design, and that these types of campaigns need to be up-scaled and applied to a broad audience. A literature review of models is completed within the categories of measurement and verification, behavioral change campaigns, project management, and strategic management to identify an approach to continuous campaign management. Determined to be the best approach for the current research, the balanced scorecard (Kaplan and Norton 1992) is adapted to a campaign perspective. Through seven expert interviews, the proposed approach is applied to seven campaigns in operation. Expert feedback of the proposed approach is recorded and compared with literature theory to gain understanding of gaps between the two. The largest gap is identified in the management of learning and innovation, both in theory and practice. Finally, an updated approach is presented based on expert feedback, and an extension of the current approach is offered by the author for future research. Clay},
